data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Remove entirely |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),
            timeout);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout",
                ex.InnerException);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException ex)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout", ex);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls for This Migration

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation isn't instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the token won't interrupt mid-execution. The `work` delegate must check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints or the task runs to completion despite the timeout. |
| **The convenience overload hides this** | The `Func<T>` overload preserves backward compatibility but the work *cannot actually be cancelled* — it just abandons the task. Prefer the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload. |
| **Blocking I/O won't respond** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read`, etc. won't wake up. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` is `IDisposable` — leaking it leaks timers. Always `using`. |

### Example: Making Work Cooperative

```csharp
// BEFORE — relied on Thread.Abort to kill this mid-loop
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
        Process(item);
    return true;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// AFTER — checks token so cancellation actually takes effect
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return true;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Uncooperative Code (No Checkpoint Possible)

If `work` calls third-party code you can't modify to accept a token, cancellation won't interrupt it. Options:

1. **Accept abandonment** — the `Func<T>` overload fires-and-forgets the task after timeout (thread leak risk).
2. **Move to a child process** — call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. This is the only reliable way to terminate uncooperative code in modern .NET.
